SIMPLE: dispirit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dispirit
<hw>Dis*pir"it</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Dispirited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Dispiriting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>dis-</ets> +
<ets>spirit</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To deprive of cheerful
spirits; to depress the spirits of; to dishearten; to
discourage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not <qex>dispirited</qex> with my afflictions.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has <qex>dispirited</qex> himself by a debauch.</q>
<rj><qau>Collier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To distill or infuse the spirit of.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This makes a man master of his learning, and <qex>dispirits</qex>
the book into the scholar.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To dishearten; discourage; deject; damp; depress;
cast down; intimidate; daunt; cow.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>dispirited</ent>⟦br⟧
